hare their experiences of working for peace and justice and discuss the obstacles to both. They address a wide range of contemporary problems, including the war on terror, killer drones, the invasions and occupations of Afghanistan and Iraq, mass surveillance, the human cost of war, political-economic impediments to peace, violent extremism, the role of women in peace-building, and the continued threat of nuclear weapons. With its stories of how peace activists found their calling and its exploration of why the world still needs peace activism, the book offers a vision rooted in human community and hope for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPacifistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPeace movementszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aPeacexCongresses. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Peace. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion and Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh1 aAmidon, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmidon, John W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntal, Chris J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAumand, Maureen Baillargeon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAumand, Maureen Baillargeon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenjamin, Medea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonpane, Blase, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreyman, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreyman, Steve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristman, Kristin Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.